						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-Atlas-of-African-Agriculture-Research-and-Development" title="The Atlas of African Agriculture Research and Development " alt="link">The Atlas of African Agriculture Research and Development </a></h2>

	
					<p>The preview of the <i>Atlas of African Agriculture Research and Development</i>, published by IFPRI in 2013, is part of a wide-ranging <i>e-Atlas initiative</i> that will showcase a variety of spatial data, &nbsp;tools, and services generated by R&amp;D practitioners working in Africa. This preview features a number of maps and data tables related to topics such as Africa’s public agriculture R&amp;D &nbsp;investments and its agriculture research pool (using ASTI data), and the footprint of agriculture, environmental and economic constraints and opportunities. Organized around 6 themes, the &nbsp;Atlas includes more than 30 data summaries, each containing mapped data and supporting text that puts the visual information in context.(HarvestChoice, 09/07/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-Atlas-of-African-Agriculture-Research-and-Development">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Climate-models-more-questions-than-answers" title="Climate models: more questions than answers" alt="link">Climate models: more questions than answers</a></h2>

	
					<p>Sonja Vermeulen of CGIAR CCAFS discusses the pertinence of current climate models, citing a recent report: ‘Implications of regional improvement in global climate models for agricultural &nbsp;impact research’.&nbsp; Vermeulen explains why models are poor at representing inter-annual variability and why they perform much better for some regions and some crops than for others. She &nbsp;argues that the ’models’ ability to represent climate is improving [...].&nbsp; However, if models are to advance sufficiently to permit assessments of future crop yields before today’s young &nbsp;scientists have retired, we need major breakthroughs in modelling approaches, not just linear improvements.’(GCIAR CCAFS, 01/07/2013)&nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Climate-models-more-questions-than-answers">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-packaging-for-Tonga-s-agriculture-export-products" title="New packaging for Tonga’s agriculture export products" alt="link">New packaging for Tonga’s agriculture export products</a></h2>

	
					<p>The Pacific Horticultural and Agricultural Market Access Project (PHAMA), with the help of the New Zealand offices of Pacific Islands Trade &amp; Invest (PT&amp;I), developed new packaging &nbsp;material (retail plastic bags) and design (of label stickers) for Tonga’s frozen root crop (cassava) products. Primarily meant to help producers meet market standards and compliance &nbsp;requirements in the New Zealand and Australian markets, the new labelling may well strengthen the competitive advantage of Tonga’s agricultural export products. Four exporting companies &nbsp;have been selected to conduct the trial run of the packaging.(Pacific Periscope, 08/07/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-packaging-for-Tonga-s-agriculture-export-products">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/European-manufacturers-to-halve-food-waste-Australian-research-quantifies-food-waste" title="European manufacturers to halve food waste, Australian research quantifies food waste" alt="link">European manufacturers to halve food waste, Australian research quantifies food waste</a></h2>

	
					<p>Representatives from across Europe’s food supply chain have committed their organizations to reducing edible food waste, in line with the European Commission’s goal of halving food waste &nbsp;by 2020. A life-cycle approach is being developed for critical products. In Australia, the study, titled ‘The role of packaging in minimising food waste in the supply chain of the future’, from &nbsp;RMIT University in Melbourne focused on where and why food waste occurs both along the fresh and processed food supply. The research identifies opportunities for industry to address food &nbsp;waste through innovative and sustainable primary, secondary and tertiary packaging</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/European-manufacturers-to-halve-food-waste-Australian-research-quantifies-food-waste">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Documentation-of-the-symposium-on-Rural-Advisory-Services" title="Documentation of the symposium on Rural Advisory Services" alt="link">Documentation of the symposium on Rural Advisory Services</a></h2>

	
					<p>On behalf of the German Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ), the GIZ Sector Project Sustainable Agriculture organised this symposium on Rural Advisory &nbsp;Services (RAS), early 2013. The documentation includes: 1) a global status report of RAS and five key areas for mobilisation; 2) Practice review lessons learned from implementation; 3) a &nbsp;summary of the panel discussion. Kristin Davis at the Global Forum for Rural Advisory Services (GFRAS) details in her report the five key factors for mobilising the potential of RAS: best fit &nbsp;approaches, pluralism, accountability, capacity development and sustainability.(GIZ, 03/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Documentation-of-the-symposium-on-Rural-Advisory-Services">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Results-and-innovations-from-transnational-research-partnerships" title="Results and innovations from transnational research partnerships" alt="link">Results and innovations from transnational research partnerships</a></h2>

	
					<p>The objective of this research fair organised in June 2013 by the Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC) and the Swiss Commission for Research Partnerships with Developing &nbsp;Countries (KFPE) was to enable exchange and dialogue between science, policy, and practice for securing global public goods in the context of sustainable development. From this page, &nbsp;you can download presentations by key staff of participating organisations on topics such as ‘Getting research and innovation into policy and practice’.In his presentation, François Münger, Head of the Global Programme on Water Initiatives at SDC, details the barriers to linking research, policy and practice, such as: Low recognition and &nbsp;rating of practice and policy influence in a academic cursus; Difference of timing between research and political rhythms which limits the possibility to take advantage of the political &nbsp;opportunities; Results often presented to potential users at the end of research project. According to him, transdisciplinary and multi-stakeholder approaches can further innovation by &nbsp;connecting researchers to larger networks or introduce them to transdisciplinary approaches that can help them think out of the box. Research partnership is an important strategic option to &nbsp;connect policy and research.(KFPE, 06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Results-and-innovations-from-transnational-research-partnerships">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Farmer-s-choice-of-seeds-in-four-EU-countries-under-different-levels-of-GM-crop-adoption" title="Farmer’s choice of seeds in four EU countries under different levels of GM crop adoption" alt="link">Farmer’s choice of seeds in four EU countries under different levels of GM crop adoption</a></h2>

	
					<p>Researcher Angelika Hilbeck at the Institute of Integrative Biology of the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology looked into the agricultural seed catalogues available to farmers in countries &nbsp;with different degrees of GM crop adoption (Austria, Germany, Spain, and Switzerland). She and her colleagues estimated how much real-world choice in seeds maize farmers have in each &nbsp;of the countries. The results show that, between 1995 and 2011, in the countries that did not adopt GM crop (Austria, Germany and Switzerland), actual restrictions and regulations of GM &nbsp;crops have not decreased seed choices/cultivar availability for farmers. In contrast, they observed that in Spain, which has adopted GM maize, the seed market was more concentrated with &nbsp;fewer differentiated cultivars on offer: the overall number of maize cultivars declined. The research also plotted the yields over the time period only to note that there was no reduction in yields &nbsp;in non-adopting countries.(Environmental Sciences Europe 2013, 25:12 doi:10.1186/2190-4715-25-12)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Farmer-s-choice-of-seeds-in-four-EU-countries-under-different-levels-of-GM-crop-adoption">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action" title="The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action" alt="link">The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action</a></h2>

	
					<p>Indices and maps of global hidden hunger are being developed to help prioritise programme assistance and to serve as an evidence-based global advocacy tool. In this research paper, &nbsp;Sumithra Muthayya of Sax Institute Sydney, Australia together with specialists from both the non-profit and for-profit nutrition sectors, creates two types of hidden hunger indices and maps &nbsp;(using data on stunting, anaemia, retinol levels and estimates of Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALYs) attributed to micronutrient deficiencies). Of note, occurrence of iodine deficiency did &nbsp;not conform to that of other micronutrients (it mainly occurs in developed countries). The study demonstrates how these indices and maps provide crucial data for tackling global multiple &nbsp;micronutrient deficiencies and could help to scale up effective nutrition interventions.(<i>PLoS ONE</i> 8(6): e67860. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0067860. June 2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Tomato-fruits-a-good-target-for-iodine-biofortification" title="Tomato fruits: a good target for iodine biofortification" alt="link">Tomato fruits: a good target for iodine biofortification</a></h2>

	
					<p>Iodine deficiency affects two billion people worldwide. This experiment conducted by the PlantLab, Italy and the private company SQM S.A., Chile evaluated the possibility of biofortifying &nbsp;tomato fruits with iodine. Results showed that the use of iodized salts induced a significant increase in the fruit’s iodine content in doses that did not affect plant growth and development. &nbsp;This suggests that the tomato is a particularly suitable crop for iodine biofortification programmes. The pattern and magnitude of iodine deficiency does not conform to that of other &nbsp;micronutrients. The greatest proportions of children with iodine deficiency are in the Eastern Mediterranean (46.6%), European (44.2%), and African (40.4%) regions. The daily Dietary &nbsp;Reference Intake (USA) for iodine is between 110 µg for infants and 290 µg for lactating mothers. Some foods are naturally rich in iodine: beans, potatoes (with skin), gray (rock) salt, sea &nbsp;vegetables (kelp), yoghurt.(<i>Front. Plant Sci.</i> 4:205. doi: 10.3389/fpls.2013.00205 ; 27/06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Tomato-fruits-a-good-target-for-iodine-biofortification">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
<p>

